  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 27.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And if any soul sin through ignorance.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " No doubt by way of omission, as in the preceding case, and thus this regulation will be distinguished from that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In either case the ritual is apparently intended to be the same, although not so fully described here. In verse 29 the benefit of the ordinance is extended to strangers; this was natural in a law which directly contemplates the residence of Israel in their permanent home. Numbers 15:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the same way, again, there was one law for the native and the stranger, in relation to sins of omission on the part of single individuals. The law laid doon in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) for the Israelites, is repeated here in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is raised into general validity for foreigners also. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", האזרח is written absolutely for לאזרח.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
